  "original_solution": "Your shadow changes size throughout the day due to the position of the sun in the sky. In the morning, when the sun is low on the horizon, shadows are long because the angle of sunlight is shallow. As the sun rises higher in the sky, the angle of sunlight becomes steeper, causing shadows to shorten. At noon, when the sun is at its highest point, shadows are at their shortest. In the afternoon, as the sun begins to set, shadows lengthen again as the angle of sunlight decreases. This phenomenon is a result of the interplay between the light source (the sun) and the object casting the shadow (you).",
